Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
A lunatic asylum, where young people are supposed to meet today.
A crypt chapel, where digging is now being done for the S-Bahn tunnel.
Allotment gardeners cultivate the former land of farmers.
The oldest official map of Munich brings exciting stories to light.
It is annoying when maps are not up-to-date.
Anyone who has ever had to get upset because the car navigation system showed a green meadow instead of a bypass road knows this.
The historical maps of the digital Bavaria Atlas, an offer of the Geoportal Bavaria of the state government, are anything but up-to-date - but therefore very revealing.
Especially when compared to current online maps.
Then it becomes clear how cities and municipalities in the distribution area of the Münchner Merkur have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavarian Atlas is a patchwork quilt that is not immediately recognizable as such.
More detailed maps, so-called original position sheets, were incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian Surveying Administration, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey in Bavaria.
Her client: Napoleon.
The French army commander occupied Bavaria since the spring of 1800 during the War of the Second Coalition with Austria.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical survey of Bavaria - of course for military purposes.
Even though the French troops finally withdrew with the Treaty of Lunéville of 9 February 1801, it was today's neighbours who created the idea of a comprehensive map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV Joseph pushed the project forward, founded the "Topographische Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The original position sheet for Munich dates from 1856 and, like all the others, can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek.
The comparison past/present is most impressive using the example of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which still appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a Munich district 21 years after the map was created, i.e. in 1877.
Today Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
Around 1856, the houses of Untersendling were concentrated along today's Plinganserstraße, which was not named until 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the uprising of the Bavarian peasants against Austria in 1705.
Where the Westpark is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: When zooming in, a smaller-scale map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: handwritten numbered parcels from the so-called "original recording", from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots no longer occupy farmers there today - but allotment gardeners of the plant "Land in Sonne".
A large green area stands out north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, the venue of the Oktoberfest since 1810, was actually still a meadow in the 19th century - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the original position sheet one reads in the area of today's district Au-Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "Auf der Lüften" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße people with delusions were once locked up.
In 1858/59 the Munich district lunatic asylum "Auf der Auer Lüften" was founded there.
From 1872, Dr. Bernhard von Gudden headed the institution - the psychiatrist who is associated with the death of King Ludwig II.
"He was progressive for his time and stopped, for example, the chaining of the so-called lunatics.
In addition, he forbade the staff to use violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, director of the Museum Haidhausen, who dealt with the institution for an exhibition.
Initially, there was room for 280 patients, later expanded to 500 places.
At some point, even this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the district insane asylum in Haar in 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost, one of the largest psychiatric hospitals in Germany, has been located there.
On the site of the former Auer Anstalt, young people now meet in Munich's Salesianum.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with training companies.
To the west is the football pitch of TSV München Ost, to the east residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's home "Casa Don Bosco" was built - architecturally based on the original building of the lunatic asylum, which had been destroyed in bombing raids during the Second World War.
The Marienplatz was listed around 1856 as "Haupt Platz", the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs tore many holes in the city center in December 1944.
One big one has remained to this day - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small commercial buildings and a crypt chapel from the Middle Ages once stood at Marienhof, where the preparatory work and the groundbreaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn trunk line will take place on 5 April 2017.
With the slider, the old map of Munich can be compared with the aerial photo of today - and fill the hole at Marienhof.
Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of People of Color has issued a warning for people of color traveling to Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is scheduled to go into effect by August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling through the state, given that a number of questionable, race-based incidents have recently occurred throughout the state and are noted here,"  says the group's opinion.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"They have violations of civil rights that happen to people.
They are stopped because of the color of their skin, they are beaten up or killed," Missouri NAACP President Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints at such a frequency that we haven't heard before."
It is the first such warning issued by the organization for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year after running out of gasoline while traveling across the state and being taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The council also points to a recent report by the Office of the Missouri Attorney General, which shows that black motorists in the state are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and inform their families, friends and co-workers about what might happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People need to be ready, whether it's bail money or letting relatives know they're traveling through the state."
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, which rank the state 16th in the country in terms of the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a business for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the U.S.
Electric fence project is elementary
