At the Rechtgrabenhof of the Schwendemann family, representatives of the Fischerbach CDU local association met together with Mayor Thomas Schneider and the two deputies.
Markus Schwendemann first provided insights into his farm, where he cultivates 55 hectares of meadows and 40 hectares of forest, cares for 40 dairy cows and as many young animals and accommodates holiday guests in five apartments.
For him, "Black Forest milk" is the marketing channel for the milk of his cows without alternative, says Schwendemann.
On the table of the holiday guests comes exclusively regional.
Since he is also BLHV chairman of Fischerbach, he described the electric fence project as "fundamentally important".
I cannot operate profitably on such steep surfaces.
The grassland area provides a lot of work, much has to be worked with the brushcutter.
"We are struggling with the conditions and the topography here," Schwendemann emphasized.
In 2003, he took over his parents' business and manages it without chemical pesticides and fertilisers, even though he does not run an organic farm.
For Mayor Thomas Schneider it was clear: "The municipality has recognized the importance of the electric fence project and is happy about the Leader funding".
At costs of EUR 3000 to EUR 4000 per hectare, farmers would have to be supported.
It is hoped that the reforestation of the areas could be delayed for quite a while.
"The greatest treasure we have are the people who work in agriculture and are concerned about how to take their business further," the mayor emphasized.
Farmers are often criticised for the support
In 2013, a total of 25 plots of eleven participants were fenced in via the electric fence subsidy.
The open area is thus 40 hectares, which may not be reforested until at least 2023.
Of the total cost of EUR 71 500, half was funded by Leader, a quarter by the municipality of Fischerbach.
This left farmers with EUR 12 610, which they had to invest in 16.2 kilometres of pasture fence.
"The big advantage is the longevity of the fences," explained Schwendemann.
Kordula Kovac stressed: "You are doing a really good job, without farmers and rural women it does not work".
For Peter Weiss it was also clear: "The best food is produced here".
The Baden-Württemberg Landscape Management Directive (LPR) enables state funding for pasture fences.
The aim is to keep the Black Forest open.
The prerequisite is the existence of a funding scheme designated by the LPR.
In addition, the area to be fenced must not be manageable by tractors (slope gradient over 35 percent) and must therefore be threatened by afforestation.
For the Fischerbacher Weidezaunprojekt 2018, the application of eight participants with 24 plots, who want to build almost 16 kilometers of fence, is currently running.
The open area corresponds to 35 hectares, the calculated costs are more than 112,000 euros.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now Trump's White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
Americans appreciate them as much as any other, hence the carefully orchestrated overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologues of the Trump regime, surely knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated dispute with CNN's Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller didn't attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he did.
But he attacked its significance, and especially the importance attributed to it, when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller insulted Acosta, "I don't want to go into a complete thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are referring to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller is factually correct, but as he himself put it, it's not really about history.
It is about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state invites not only any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tired, your poor, / your afflicted masses who long to breathe freely, / the miserable waste of your rich shores."
There has never been a time when the "miserable waste" was better visible on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism – he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's US.
This conflict over the significance of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural dispute: it is indeed a conflict over the importance of America.
Lazarus—and her friends, who worked to place her words at the grassroots level after her death—knew very well that they were performing a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The poem's association with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people from the right wing had long wanted to change it back.
The great screamer Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty did not invite anyone, but rather was an early neoconservative bringing the American flame to the deranged world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
It is intended to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not meant to light the way to the United States."
Quite unusually, Limbaugh has come across something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of the point of view of perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see her as seen by the exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
It's literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they must hear.
And, of course, that's not the perspective Miller and Trump ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not intended to light the way, but to ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
