Blocking critics via Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't stand heating up voters
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn't long before the newspapers beat him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
He scolded the criticism, sure.
But he has not silenced his critics.
For in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, stupid and dumb, we will be led like sheep to slaughter."
That brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's associates have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online commentary was full of a backlash with "So what?"
"It's just Facebook," many people said.
But it is important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state that is amazingly popular.
He has the second-highest approval rating of the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in the management of his state and strict adherence to the principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as the primary means of connecting with his constituents and playfully debuting his hairless head on his site after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor's side — which is a public forum labeled official and employees paid with public tax dollars — is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people wielding the whip online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said that their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not profane.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md., was not hateful, but she asked about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other breaking news," she wrote in the comments section of The Post.
"I don't appreciate this idea either, if a number of people take a stand on the same issue, then they are more likely to be disregarded by some as a so-called collective effort and not recognized as a large group of affected citizens."
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack," others would likely call "advocacy."
The Facebook era makes it easy to crop a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than in the past if the same thing had been done that employees were sent to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or to arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticized for berating Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones on this issue fell last week in Virginia.
The chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
That shouldn't be so hard.
At Washington's time, the era of affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers lashed out at his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people who used pseudonyms like "Juricola," "Valerius," "Belisarius," and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers that struck down Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticizing his stance on the Treaty of Amity, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected from the George Washington Project's online papers.
But he did not silence them.
Freedom of speech, disagreement, and discourse are the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
