Visitors to the sixth charity serenade can be enchanted by this powerful place.
The Friends and Supporters of Tumlingen have made the rescue and preservation of the oldest building in the village their concern.
Walter Martini emphasizes: "It is a unique village gem."
In 1267, the St. Hilarius Chapel was first mentioned in the Württemberg Book of Deeds: Count Hermann von Sulz sold "the hill with the parish church of Tumlingen including the Vogtei" to Magister Eberhard von Horb and his brother Dietrich for 20 marks of silver.
According to the wording of the document, in addition to the former parish church, there was also a stately farm on the Tumlinger Berg, to which the church or the patronage right belonged and not vice versa.
So there were also people living there.
As can be seen from the description of the Oberamt Freudenstadt from 1858, in addition to the lower village and the upper village, which can still be seen today in the townscape of Tumlingen, the "mountain" was the third, the stately settlement core of the village.
Old maps from around the year 1600 underpin these historical facts.
The right of patronage arose from the early medieval church law.
A gentleman who built, equipped and staffed a church with a pastor remained the owner of this church and could also bequeath this own church.
Associated with this was the right to appoint a pastor or to propose a new pastor to the bishop.
There were three altars in the church and two bells on the tower.
The larger of the two broke up at Christmas 1673.
The newly acquired bell sounded for the first time in 1692, but had to be handed over later during the Second World War in 1942.
In the 30-year war (1616 to 1648) the windows were smashed and the bell ropes stolen.
The roof was leaking.
In 1796, French troops camped near the church.
They broke out the pulpit and church chairs and used them as firewood.
Remains of the church threatened to collapse in 1809.
Until 1869, the Hilarius Cemetery in Tumlingen also served as the final resting place for the dead from Hörschweiler.
In 1823 the cemetery was expanded and the Hilariuskirche demolished.
Only the church tower was left standing.
On New Year's Eve 1834, a storm split the church tower and half of it collapsed.
To prevent a disaster, the tower was demolished.
Only the tower dwarf, which still exists today, has been preserved as a witness to the 750-year-old church history.
Today, Horst Kallenberger and Rolf-Dieter Wasem of the "Schaffigen Rentnern" succeed Dieter Dockhorn in maintaining the Hilarius complex.
As organizers, the Friends and Sponsors of Tumlingen invite you to the sixth serenade on Sunday, July 16, in the old cemetery of St. Hilariuskapelle.
This will be designed by the combo of the Kepler-Gymnasium Freudenstadt and with contributions by Kurt Kübler and Reinhold Matteis.
Village leader Hartmut Romann gives the final word.
The program starts at 4.30 pm.
Doors open at 3:30 p.m.
At the end of the serenade, a drink will take place in front of the cemetery.
"Enjoy a summer evening under the shade of old trees and with the wide view over meadows to the forest", the organizers emphasize the fantastic view.
The serenade takes place only in dry weather.
The organizers hope for many supporters for the preservation of the historic St. Hilarius complex, which is important for Tumlingen and Hörschweiler.
The friends and supporters of Tumlingen feel particularly committed to the preservation of the homeland, as Serenade organizer Walter Martini affirms.
