Moore's Ford Massacre: Activists Repeat Racist Lynching as Call for Justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove through a group of spectators in rural Monroe, Georgia, and rumbled toward Moore's Ford Bridge.
Before the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns stepped forward to block its path.
The leader of the mob - a middle-aged man in a pinstripe suit - took a long drag on his cigar and looked through the windshield.
Inside, the inmates hovered in fear.
"We want this n ---- Roger!" the man yelled.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams broke the silence as a young black man was dragged from the passenger seat.
Luckily, this horrific scene, played out on July 22, is just a re-enactment.
But when a noose is thrown around the neck of "Roger", almost everyone in the audience lets out very real sighs.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to recreate the night two black couples—Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murray Dorsey—were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
No one was ever charged with the murders.
"It's really unbelievable that not a single person has been arrested in all these years — even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are," said Tyrone Brooks, who helps organize the reenactment.
"It's a stain of dirt on a story, but it's a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist.
For him, the re-enactment serves as a dramatic call to action and represents an annual reminder to the Monroe community that an injustice has never been corrected.
"We want law enforcement, we want the end, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we need justice," he said.
"We cannot achieve healing and reconciliation until we receive justice."
A coroner lays a sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Moore-Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspected in the lynching trial.
But no one has ever been charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, civil rights activists say the dual motivation for lynching has always been known throughout the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote in the summer primary campaign for the first time.
At about the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black tenant Roger Malcolm stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight — allegedly over a woman.
Brooks said the rumor in town was that Hester had slept with Malcom's wife, Dorothy, and that the baby she was carrying was not from her husband.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to free Malcolm from prison, according to the FBI.
He was escorted to prison by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they moved away from the prison and approached Moore's Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
"As it turns out, it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the murders," concludes an FBI report.
"It is also evident that there was a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement, who were not only involved in the murders, removing evidence and covering up the identities of witnesses."
Brooks puts it even more succinctly.
"It was a suffrage massacre," he said.
"They were all killed to send a message to black people in this community: 'If you register and if you vote, this is going to happen to you.'
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene directed the annual re-enactment of the Moore Ford Bridge Lynch murders.
Their portrayal is vivid, poignant, and grounded in a kind of deep racism that many would have you believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch, and even harder to look away, but Greene said that's the point.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because then we will be confronted with its ugliness in all of us," she said.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you don't want to listen to me or don't want to hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors—a dozen whites and the rest blacks—crowded into a room and listened as Greene launched a well-rehearsed overview of the play.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's co-director here.
He has played the role of chief clan member for years, but he said the role never gets easier.
"I feel dirty because I'm not like that," Marbaugh said.
"But I think it's very important to keep this story alive because we don't want to go back to those times."
On the other side of the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, rehearsed their lines.
The play begins with Malcolm yelling at Hester and harassing him, angry that he slept with his wife, Dorothy.
"I said, --- he, get away from my property!"
Rascona returns fire.
There is a break.
And then everyone (at least all black actors) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What?!" asked Rascona.
He is alarmed and confused.
Was I too hard?
"No," Greene said, still giggling.
"I just don't think white people said 'n --- he' back then."
