Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on acquiring players, but they must counteract with legitimate sources of income that allow them to break even in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA President in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had taken on huge debts in their pursuit of success effectively cheated and risked ruining themselves if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from focusing on club debt to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich originally used at Chelsea in 2003 – buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the team and build a global brand – was to become a tougher affair.
During the current three-year FFP assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can accept losses of 30 million euros.
And although Platini fell out of favor from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Aleksander Ceferin, remains committed to discouraging excessive spending.
"Certainly FFP is not dead and we will certainly strengthen the rules for the future," Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar's buy-out clause in a lump sum, it can spread the amount for invoicing over the duration of his contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so that the transfer fee for the next five years in the amount of 44.4 million euros can be shown in the annual financial statements.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 hit PSG with the heaviest sanctions, along with Manchester City-owned Abu Dhabi.
PSG were fined €60 million ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to €20 million – and it was ordered that team members for the 2014/15 Champions League be limited to 21 players instead of the usual 25 players.
UEFA is looking for clubs that could try to outwit its financial regulator by inflating their revenues through companies linked to a club's owners.
While a Qatari company could sponsor PSG if the value of the sponsorship were to exceed standard market rates, UEFA would not consider this legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of PSA's sponsorship was inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It has been reported that part of PSG's payments to Neymar could come via payments from the 2022 World Cup organising committee in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become World Cup ambassadors and such a manoeuvre could be easy for UEFA regulators to figure out.
The sanctions against PSG so far mean that UEFA will be even more attentive to any attempt to circumvent the rules.
