NHS (National Health Service) to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will have access to 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September following a battle in High Court against funding of the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that pre-sex pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 per cent, is now being delivered by the Health Service via an initial three-year study for an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the process after the Court of Appeal last year upheld a Supreme Court ruling that the NHS had the authority to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England chief Simon Stevens as an "important new intervention", while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a "pivotal moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to register, with more clinics to follow in October before it will be rolled out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a sequence of HIV supplements taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there is just enough medication in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day or so already two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals, and those with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics identify eligible participants who agree with the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also register for possible participation in their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the medicines this week following an international competitive procurement.
The study aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence of how it is targeted, uptaken and implemented at scale.
Stevens said: "This major new intervention should complement and overhaul the wide-ranging and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of sustained progress in addressing one of humanity's greatest health challenges."
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said: "This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at needy and vulnerable people, offers the opportunity to change the English HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, Chief Executive Officer of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: "The priority now must be to ensure that the trial is carried out quickly across the country and that no one at risk for HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP testing medicine has been procured, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people living with HIV."
Sharon Hodgson, shadow health secretary, said: "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and delayed implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and can end the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This trial brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it is important that this study is carried out across the country as soon as possible to protect individuals who are infected with HIV and that it will help us get one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society'.
