Antarctica: Gigantic iceberg drifts in Antarctica
In West Antarctica, a gigantic iceberg almost seven times the size of Berlin has broken away from the ice shelf.
This was announced by the Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research in Bremerhaven on Wednesday.
The colossus, which weighs over a trillion tons and is 5800 square kilometers in size, is now drifting north and will probably take two or three years to melt.
With a length of 175 kilometres and a width of up to 50 kilometres, it is one of the largest ice giants that researchers have registered in the past three decades.
It does not pose a danger to humans.
The extent to which climate change has played a role in the break-off of the iceberg is unclear, according to researchers.
Overall, however, there has been a series of unusual collapses of ice shelves in the region for about 30 years, writes the US Research Center for Snow and Ice (NSIDC) in a factual background.
According to many researchers, this could be related to global warming.
The now broken off colossus was previously part of the Larsen C Ice Shelf.
Ice shelf floats on the sea and is fed by large glaciers.
It thus grows further and further into the sea and breaks off regularly.
The Larsen C Ice Shelf lies south of South America almost at the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
North of this ice shelf, the balance of growth and breaking was disturbed a few years ago.
A complete ice shelf has disintegrated there, writes AWI researcher Daniela Jansen.
There is some evidence that the Larsen C ice shelf is also in danger, because the front edge has never retreated as far as it does now.
In addition, the ice sheet is under tension and can disintegrate if a piece breaks off at a key point.
The melting of ice shelves and icebergs does not raise sea levels, as they float on the water and ice displaces as much water as it yields after melting itself.
However, the loss of the ice shelf means that the glaciers flow directly into the sea and can drain much faster than before.
This could possibly raise sea levels, but only to a small extent, writes the British research project for the observation of Antarctica (Midas).
According to AWI, the Larsen C Ice Shelf is the fourth largest ice shelf in Antarctica with almost 50,000 square kilometres.
At the transition from the mainland it is up to 700 meters thick, at the front edge to the open ocean about 200 meters.
There it breaks off regularly.
"Although it is a natural occurrence and we are not aware of any direct link to climate change, the ice sheet is now in a more vulnerable position," said Martin O'Leary of Swansea University in the UK.
"This is the furthest retreat since records began," he confirmed.
It is controversial among scientists whether the Larsen C ice shelf will now grow again or decline in the long term and possibly collapse, said his colleague Adrian Luckman, adding: "Our models say it will be less stable."
But this development will take decades.
Even if these researchers do not attribute the collapse of this gigantic iceberg to climate change, many ice shelves on the Antarctic Peninsula have disintegrated in recent decades.
This long corner of Antarctica stretches towards South America.
According to data from the British Antarctic Survey, the ice surface of the Antarctic Peninsula has declined by 28,000 square kilometres since the 1950s.
The rise in temperature contributed to the decline.
The Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by around three degrees in the past 50 years, making it one of the areas where the temperature is rising the fastest.
