The murder of a journalist underscores the growing threat in Mexico
Staff at the weekly Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to review their plans for covering the recent chaos in Sinaloa State caused by organized crime, corrupt officials and incessant drug wars.
But that day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to talk about security.
They were told that it is important to change their routines.
Two high-ranking journalists discuss what feels safer: to take their children, who were the target of a grenade attack in 2009, to the office, or leave them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a blackboard at the front of the room: adversaries, neutrals, allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column – no proof is needed, perceptions and gut feelings are enough.
There are drug smugglers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being on the payroll of the government or the cartels, a catalogue of criminals who make the chaos of Mexico dangerous.
There is no respite from the violence, and as corpses pile up across the country, more and more journalists are on the scene: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012. 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats, and so far this year there have been at least seven deaths in seven states.
Among the latter is its editor and inspiration of Riodoce, co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence is present everywhere - a large photo of Valdez showing his middle finger with the word "Justice" hangs on the façade of the Riodoce building. Two reporters in their thirties, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts showing his smiling face with glasses or his typical Panama hat.
The workshop takes place less than two months after his death, and the reporters discuss their shared topics, the trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was established in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, it has opened only two criminal cases, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organized crime each year, the killers are rarely brought to justice by journalists.
In Riodoce's case, they still insist on dealing with the violence of Sinaloa, even though they are heartbroken and even though the terrain is now even more treacherous.
Without information about the murderers, without justice, the meeting to discuss security is of little use, Ibarra says.
"It's very stupid to waste my time in this workshop," he says.
"As long as we don't know why, we distrust everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the office of the newspaper Riodoce in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men. He was forced out of his car and shot 12 times, presumably because of the name of the newspaper - which translates as "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove away in his car and damaged it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumors tend to fly freely in Culiacan.
But on the subject of Valdez, there is practically nothing but silence.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa had become one of the bloodiest battlefields in the country as rival factions fight here to fill the vacuum.
It doesn't matter that in Sinaloa every day someone or more people are shot on the street, or that the cemetery is full of ornate, two-story mausoleums for drug kingpins that are larger than many houses for the living.
Forget for a minute that there is a state of "calm" when only one cartel has control over the coastal state with its valuable ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
Despite this, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez (60), a co-founder and director of Riodoce, is broken with the guilt of not being able to protect his friend.
He believes two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First, in February, there was the publication of an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival antitrust factions in the war with Guzman's sons.
This publication may have angered the sons, suspected gang members bought up every copy of the issue as soon as it was delivered to newsstands.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a milestone in Mexican violence against journalists.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be there.
He was a veteran reporter for Noroeste in 2003 when he teamed up with five colleagues to form Riodoce and sold $50 in holdings.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without encountering the drug problem," Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for its bold and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved being able to publish hard-hitting research without fear of censorship, and readers were intrigued by a publication where they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after founding Riodoce, she received the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Prize for her reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the Committee to Protect Journalists' International Press Freedom Award for his courage in prosecuting the Mexican drug story wherever it took him.
He voluntarily admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to go on living," he said at the time of the CPJ award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa "is a way of life," he said in an interview with Rompeviento-TV last October.
"You have to take on the task that falls to you as a journalist - either that or you play the stupid one.
I don't want to be asked, "What have you done in the face of so many deaths... Why didn't you say what was going on?"
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the joker who could curse like a dockworker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted in his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit at the same table.
Now they ask: Was his love of routine his undoing?
His death has also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their jobs while staying alive.
"They don't like it when you deal with their wives, their children, their clean shops, their secret runways" to move drugs.
"These things weren't allowed," Bojorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, is a high degree of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trust your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble, said the editor of the Riodoce Andres Villarreal, is that "smell is a sense that can be deceived ... and then the thing happened to Javier."
The old rules, as he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa – nor do they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodoce employees met for safety training, cell phones were suddenly not allowed. Days earlier, it was revealed that spyware sold exclusively to governments was being used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two police officers sought shelter from the heat of 104 degrees (40 ° C) in the shade of a tree.
They were contracted by the state government to protect Riodoce's offices in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood of Culiacan.
Half-jokingly, some of the reporters wondered if these officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself described as untrustworthy.
