Dinosaurs used camouflage to dodge their enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Now, researchers have found that the initial findings of a Canadian miner's incredible rhino have been so well preserved that experts have described it as "Mona Lisa the dinosaur."
It was so well preserved that they could even determine that its scaly skin was of reddish brown - and they said it had something of a "troubled past".
The report in the journal Current Biology called it "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found, and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
The fossil is a newly discovered type of nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has stunned researchers who describe it as "truly remarkable."
According to reports in National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk while digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He encountered something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500-pound (1,100 kg) lump of soil.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be revealed.
"If you blink your eyes just a little, you could almost believe it was sleeping," said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature can be seen.
"It will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of the dinosaur."
Researchers have found that although this herbivore, despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking shell, it was likely threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a shielding technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend better with its environment and dodge its enemies, experts say, suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor about its body.
They discovered counter-shading, a common method of defense in the animal kingdom, meaning that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although counter-shading is common, the results are surprising, as the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of animals alive today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was chased by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored the obfuscation of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that use counter-shading — think deer, zebra, or armadillos — are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, signaling that this nodosaur faced a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predator behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Critical Period must have been," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to examine the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved gut contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it got into a river and was driven out into the sea, where it sank on its back to the bottom of the sea.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they are today.
"This nodosaur is really remarkable because it's completely covered with preserved scaly skin, but it also preserves in three dimensions and retains the animal's original shape," Brown said.
"The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don't need to use much imagination to reconstruct it. If you just squint your eyes a little, you could almost believe he's asleep."
The Cretaceous was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the king of them, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 m) long, six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta sank into the sea after death and was mummified in the mud.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk while digging at the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it's the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is complete from snout to hip.
The creatures averaged about 18 feet (5 meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
It contained two 20-inch-long tips protruding from his shoulders.
The researchers believe the armored herbivore washed through western Canada until a flooded river flooded it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover bumpy armor plates along the dinosaur.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, such a level of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it gets.
Fossilized remnants of the skin still cover the bumpy armor plates that support the animal's skull.
His right forefoot is at his side, his five fingers are spread upwards.
I can count the scales on its sole'.
