Deutsche Bahn: Group tests "comfort check-in"
It's a moment that almost everyone has experienced before: Unsuspectingly, you sit on the train and sleep.
Or you are immersed in your work and just have a brilliant thought.
And then: puff.
If the conductor comes and wakes you up rudely or tears the passenger out of the middle of the workflow.
Ticket control.
But the days of interruptions will soon be over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing conductorless ticket inspection.
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and validate the ticket.
A test operation is currently underway on two routes.
"If the offer is well received, we expand it.
It is then expected to be available at the beginning of next year on many other long-distance routes in Germany," said a railway spokesman.
"Comfort check-in" is what Deutsche Bahn calls ticket validation without a conductor.
In order to use them, however, some requirements must be met: You need a smartphone or a tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket - which most passengers already do.
You also have to have bought it via the Deutsche Bahn app, DB Navigator, which is the most convenient way to book tickets anyway.
And finally, you need a seat reservation.
Because the "comfort check-in" works like this: You get on the train, call up your ticket under "My tickets".
For the test customers, a button for electronic validation will then appear.
The train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y.
If the train conductor arrives at seat Y at the ticket inspection, he knows that there is a passenger sitting there with an already validated online ticket.
So you can continue to sleep, continue to work, keep silent.
The "check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn should benefit the passengers.
"If you want to travel relaxed without ticket control by our train attendants, simply check in yourself in the DB Navigator.
This enables passengers to personalise their travel time on the train," says Michael Peterson, Chief Marketing Officer of DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: "And our employees have more time than today to respond to individual customer needs."
Anyone who often travels by train knows that, in addition to delays and missed trains, ticket checks are among the biggest annoyances.
Because often you yourself, but in any case one of the fellow travelers do not have all the documents you need to validate online tickets.
Either the credit card or the identity card or any other document that you have to show is missing.
The result is endless discussions between conductor and passenger, which leads to a bad mood in the compartment or open space and delays in checking one's own ticket and takes the conductor the time to take care of other concerns at the end.
Only a small number of test customers can still use the new service.
And that only on the connections ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen.
Other train numbers on the same route have not yet been activated.
How an activist came to learn the answer to the question: "Whose Streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native sat on the bed of an Airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone in high school.
"The police have just killed an 18-year-old child, and he is still lying on the street," it said.
Confused, since no one else had posted the information on her feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on their timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was about to tweet live the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body stretched out on the street and would stay there for four hours.
"That's wild," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police tape and people screaming, and of a man claiming to be Brown's father carrying a sign that read, "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed in which a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another policeman unlocked his rifle and shouted, "I will... Animals kill everyone."
"That's not common," Ferrell recalled of her statement.
"This is not the kind of murder we've become accustomed to and can call typical."
At that moment I felt chills.
I was angry and cried."
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", in theaters starting on September 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience that exists from the point of view of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and matching crown, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before that morning "about the black experience and the black state."
"You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled of what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take them with me," Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a culmination of ... what happened in the past.
She needs to know it and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also know the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution and what we must do to become free, to liberate ourselves.
Even though I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she personally doesn't experience blatant racism, she's no different from the next black woman-child.
I feel like I'm doing her a disservice by keeping her away."
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a location opposite the police department that became a camp area as activists waited for Officer Darren Wilson to be indicted.
There, Ferrell and her daughter bonded with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism totally changed after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food equity and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all happened."
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
A question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or are you trying to find a story that you can exploit?"
This skepticism was fueled by countless cases of people, often whites — in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that people who were born and raised in Ferguson didn't center their voices and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had previously worked with then-co-director Damon Davis, an artist known for his activism around death row inmates.
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals, the team of "Whose Streets?" followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or talks to us. We're talking," Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed."
The goal wasn't to focus on Ferrell's experience — to show that the movement is "not a messiah leader, but a community coming together," Folayan said — she proved to be the film's most open participant.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, how she falls in love and marries her wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I understood that there has to be a certain vulnerability in this work and in humanizing black people."
Moreover, Ferrell's story repeats the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders who shaped the movie "BlacklivesMatter" on social media after the killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement as a whole," Ferrell said, "and so we're constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of everything."
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really sustained by black women and many black women."
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action" where Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who shook up that energy," she said.
"It's no coincidence, even though she was on the front line, because there's so much at stake in living at these intersections as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen."
Meanwhile, the news cameras in Ferguson are long gone, but the racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is on probation for 21/2 years for blocking a highway at a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area, which she calls home: "A chaos".
Nevertheless, she clings to a song and she feels committed to this memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains."
