A fitting similarity: artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room of the Fridman Gallery in New York are many faces - white, black and brown, which almost imperceptibly resemble each other - hanging from the ceiling on cables.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek swabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the excerpts from Fort Leavenworth, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year prison sentence after making classified diplomatic reports public via the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose conviction was commuted by Barack Obama when he had only three days left in office.
Dewey-Hagborg, through the algorithmic analysis of DNA extracted by Manning and from which 30 portraits were created of what someone might look like with this genomic data, has created a sharp, if somewhat intellectual, commentary not only on the malleability of DNA data—the many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations—but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has spoken openly about identifying as a woman since puberty, was convicted in 2013 of 20 charges, including six espionage law violations, computer fraud and theft.
Her image was suppressed by prison, so much so that there was only one photo — a grainy, black-and-white selfie in which Manning sits visibly uncomfortable in a driver's seat wearing a platinum blonde wig — with which she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg had just returned from the huge success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum by extracting the DNA from the waste to create an image of what these people might look like.
That's when she received an email from a newspaper magazine.
"They did an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some kind of portrait to accompany this article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't be visited at that time and she couldn't be photographed, so they contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to take a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became disparate pen pals who exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic strip "Suppressed Images" illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which foresaw a future in which the president would change Chelsea's judgment and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually demand Manning's release after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas just days after the book was published was a welcome kind of happy encounter.
There's also something deep and strong about the opening of the exhibition now, as Donald Trump wages a war against government whistleblowers and transgender troops to find new, tweetable ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to fix.
When asked about the strange timing of all these things, Dewey-Hagborg said that "things happen for a reason."
In an artistic statement written on the wall of the gallery, Manning, with her oversized signature underneath (the "i" in her family name is marked with a heart), called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation based on gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite wall is their mitochondrial DNA sequence - a centipede of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
By including the 200 letters (or nucleotides according to the artist's sophisticated scientific lexicon), Dewey-Hagborg hoped to show how amazingly similar, at least in biological terms, we all are.
"What people will hopefully take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is," said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Spurious Memories, is also on display.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so that's 30 of those stories."
The last piece in the exhibition, which is kept in its own room, is a page from the above-mentioned comic novella.
She shows Manning emerging from the disciplinary arenas of the United States, such as King-Kong, with a speakerphone in her hand.
"If they sideline your speech, then they have won," they say.
"So never shut up."
"It came straight out of a letter she wrote me," said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
"I still get goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibit in person yet — as anticipated in the comic book — but if she does, she'll be greeted in the middle of the room by the masks, by her own genomic simulacra huddled together like hordes of protesters.
This was also targeted, like everything in the exhibition, down to the height (5" 2, Manning's stature), where their genetic haplogroups were written in pencil.
"In the past, I had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was behind their liberation."
