Creating a Comic Novel: A Castle in the History of England
In its recent past, the small Scotney Castle was featured in a squeeze music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has experienced 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy seat in Kent's Bewl River Valley and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired Yorkshireman with a penchant for historical documents.
"I think it's so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who has been dead for 300 years," he says wistfully.
"What a personal relationship to hold this letter in my hand."
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the age of Edward and documents the families who lived in Scotney. Each story was illustrated by a different, emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It's not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he wrote 'Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories' in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library – a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I only reacted this way to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins," he says.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell of smoke, because back then a fire was lit because of the light.
For someone who lives 300 years later, the smell has an effect, as if he himself were also there.
Oh, I love archives!"
For someone who is so battered with old papers that he is supported by the National Trust and the Arts Council England and lived in a castle for almost four months ("To be honest, I overrated my welcome a little"), this all seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, perusing the archives and studying the castle's many treasures and curiosities, such as the hyena heads mounted on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the moat.
He wandered through the grounds and ruins of the old castle and talked to landscapers, gardeners and sometimes the artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then, at night, he drank "whiskey and started writing."
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain full access until 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, employees were just beginning to take care of the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years of aristocrats saying, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You might think that land conflicts would be boring," says Rhodes, "but there was a birch tree that two families fought over.
Boys, let everything go!"
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into English history on a broader basis, including 'The Labourer' following a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that occurred at the castle in 1380 in this book called 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,'" says Rhodes.
"The peasant uprising started in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle's history – such as 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit priest the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts 18th century smuggler Arthur Darrell, staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery that wasn't made until years later when his coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite Scotney family: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women – I think of them as a bunch of good-looking guys, with a talent for courting heiresses."
After the end of his assignment in the castle, Rhodes is looking for other unique writing experiences
He spent two weeks in the Finnish wilderness for a graphic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th-century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave," he says.
It was like, "Oh, now I have to deal with the damn life again."
