And he still enjoys his work, as he conveys in the press conference.
He reports on varied, but also demanding tasks that await his successor.
At the same time, he is surprised that so far no application meets the requirements profile.
The city is looking for an architect or civil engineer as soon as possible.
Thus, taking into account the regular notice periods, there should still be enough time for familiarization.
Since Haslach acts as a lower building law authority for the administrative community, the applicant must have corresponding degrees.
Because the city wants to keep this function in any case.
If she were no longer able to fill it out, the citizens would have to travel to Offenburg for consultation.
But proximity to citizens is important to the city and to himself, says Wacker, who reports a good working atmosphere and a good atmosphere between the authorities and citizens.
In more than 30 years in office, several important projects have accumulated that Wacker looks back on with pride.
"We make the city worth living in," he says of the building authority and his employees.
But varied projects are also on the agenda in the future: The redesign of the former Hukla site and the Niederhofen car park, for example, have been initiated.
The Kinzig Bridge between Bollenbach and Steinach is being renewed, and the stadium renovation is still an issue.
The latter alone will cost around 1.5 million euros "if we do it right," Wacker estimates.
"All in all, great tasks await my successor.
It's fun to work here."
In terms of design, there is great scope for a city architect.
With Haslach's own building yard and nursery, many things can be responded to quite flexibly.
"You can achieve a lot," says Wacker, and the design of the green spaces is often praised by citizens and visitors.
Since the old town as an ensemble is a listed building, it is important to "keep an eye on what fits in" when new buildings are approved, emphasizes the outgoing city architect.
In any case, the city architect bears a great deal of responsibility.
He is the client, "in the end, everything here runs over my table".
He can count on long-standing employees for support and coordination: Markus Neumaier (structural engineering) has been with us for ten years, Manfred Schöner (civil engineering) for 15 years.
Wacker also hopes that his successor will stay for a long time: "We are looking for someone who really identifies with the position and wants to stay."
Because continuity is not only important for a good working atmosphere, but also for the further design of the city.
According to the city of Haslach, anyone who wants to succeed Roland Wacker should have completed a degree in engineering or a bachelor's degree in architecture and have good specialist knowledge in the areas of building regulations and construction planning law.
The city building authority is responsible for building and civil engineering, urban land use planning, land acquisition matters, administration of municipal properties, municipal depot with building yard and city nursery as well as lower building law authority including monument protection.
