Funding for town centre III
If you want to renovate your aging house, you will soon be able to get support from the state.
Mayor Albert Schindler and three representatives of STEG Stadtentwicklung informed about this on Wednesday in Empfingen.
At the beginning of the information event, Schindler once again gave a review of what has happened so far.
Since 1991 there have been redevelopment areas in Empfingen.
At that time, in redevelopment area I from 1991 to 2004, the state of Baden-Württemberg still took over two-thirds of the funding amount.
In redevelopment area II from 2005 to 2016, the subsidy was still 60 percent.
For Schindler, the renovations so far are a "successful project" - after all, it is important to promote interior development and not just to open up new building areas.
On April 4, the Regional Council of Karlsruhe received the information that there would be a redevelopment area III.
The funding amounts to EUR 833 333, of which EUR 500 000 comes from the Land and the remainder from the municipality of Empfingen.
How is a redevelopment area created?
According to Schindler, it will be investigated where the "really old" houses are.
However, it also plays a role whether there is any interest in rehabilitating in the planned area.
If necessary, the territorial boundaries could then shift again.
On Wednesday evening, STEG was represented by Martin Keller, Gaby Pietzschmann and Sarah Gotzel.
Keller presented the contents of the federal-state program "Social City", within the framework of which the renovations would then be carried out.
The core of the programme is the revitalisation of inner cities, the improvement of living and working conditions and the maintenance and expansion of infrastructure.
The measures would be carried out on a property-by-property basis, i.e. per plot.
The redevelopment area would then eventually be defined as a statute.
The approval period for the funding runs from 1 January 2017 to 30 April 2026.
By September of this year, however, the inventory would first be carried out, during which those involved in the redevelopment area would receive a questionnaire to fill out.
If possible, the statutes should be adopted in November or December so that the renovations can begin next year.
Pietzschmann then explained that each municipality must carry out the said preliminary investigations.
The aim is to assess the urban development deficiencies and to decide when to renovate and to what extent.
A remediation note will then also be entered in the land register for the respective property.
Pietzschmann herself would come back to Empfingen and get an idea of the situation, she promised.
Gotzel emphasized that a key success factor for the project is the participation of those involved.
Therefore, there will be questionnaires that will be sent to citizens by post in the coming weeks and can be completed until after the end of the summer holidays.
The yellow questionnaire is the "building and land sheet", which deals with the structural condition and the renovation intentions, among other things.
In the grey questionnaire, the "household and apartment sheet", information on the size, layout and occupants of a living space can be provided.
The blue "company return" is only to be completed if business premises are operated in the building.
However, it should be noted, Gotzel pointed out, that a completed questionnaire is not at the same time an application for funding.
In addition, new construction measures are not eligible for funding.
Schindler also emphasized that the distribution of subsidies works on a "first-come, first-served basis" - first come, first served.
You can't "reserve" subsidies for later.
Finally, photos of the project "Ortskern II" were shown in order to make a renovation "tasty" to those present.
