Roll backwards: The city hires 46 kitchen helpers
The city organizes the kindergarten lunch again itself.
With fixed contact persons for the children and an assignment to the team.
In the city's day-care centres, the clock is being turned back.
On 1 September, the city of Krefeld will again take over the food supply in the municipal day care centres (Kitas) on its own.
For Sonja Pommeranz, deputy head of the youth welfare department, this is good news: "We were all very happy".
Cooking continues to take place outside the home: A caterer takes over this task and delivers freshly cooked food chilled.
The city operates 46 daycare centers in the Krefeld area, in 44 the children get a warm meal at lunchtime.
In the past kindergarten year, 2800 children sat at the tables, and the demand is growing steadily.
"In the meantime, not only children who are cared for 45 hours a week eat lunch in the kindergarten," explains Pommeranz.
"The offer also applies to 35-hour care if children stay until 2 p.m."
46 part-time employees will be on kitchen duty from 1 September: they heat the delivered food, supplement it with salad, raw vegetables and fruit, portion the meal individually, serve the food, clear away, wash and clean the kitchen.
"The employees are permanently assigned to a daycare center," says Pommeranz.
The size - there are two-group as well as seven-group facilities - decides on the number of hours.
"The kitchen helpers are now an integral part of the daycare team," says Pommeranz with satisfaction.
"So they are much more involved and it is easier for the kindergarten management to implement pedagogical concepts."
Because that's what it's all about: healthy nutrition and cooking lessons.
"The children should help to prepare the food".
The direct connection of the kitchen staff to the team makes sense.
Also for the children.
"They have a well-known force in the daycare center, a person who is familiar to them, and not constantly changing people."
This continuity is important for the children.
The cleaning of the kindergarten rooms - previously also the task of the kitchen staff - will be carried out by special cleaning staff in the future.
This variant - the separation of cleaning and kitchen service - has, in addition to improving the quality of kitchen performance, also the charm that it has turned out to be the most economical for the city in the cost comparison between self-management and outsourcing, according to the press office.
And this despite the fact that 46 part-time employees are being hired.
"But these hours are not so important for around 750 people in the education sector," says Sonja Pommeranz.
Afghan democracy depends on women's political role, UN says
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the United Nations mission, said hundreds of women will run in provincial council elections. Three women are running for vice president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved in all parts of the electoral process.
Afghan elections for the provincial council and presidential elections will take place on 5 April.
The Taliban have issued threats against an electoral process that coincide with the transition from international combat operations to an advisory role.
This year, for the first time, elections will peacefully transfer power from one democratically elected government to the next.
Haysom said a strong role for women will reinforce Afghanistan's democratic success.
Afghanistan's Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters are registered.
