GMB concerned about investment at McVitie factory in Glasgow
A union wants to check with managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie about the long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company had remained silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which produces hobnobs and rich tea biscuits, among other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and union representatives would be "the first to know" when their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's store manager, GMB Scotland urged McVitie's to "raise concerns that funding for the modernisation of production lines is not being pushed forward".
GMB Senior Organiser Drew Duffy said: "The fact that we are unable to gain clarity from the General Site Manager on the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily concentrated in the local community and the greater Glasgow area, an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, from the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, the rising cost of living and the chronic decline in production, the east end of Glasgow desperately needs a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie."
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: "The store manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland just yesterday and the company will respond directly as we appreciate the continued engagement of employees and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, where some issues were discussed openly.
We discussed with employees that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our businesses – and this applies to all our businesses and locations – in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise Tollcross's heritage as a manufacturing facility and should our operations at the site change, employees and their union representatives will be the first to know."
Did PSG Barcelona warn against Neymar three years ago?
La Liga's website may regret its interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not relent in their pursuit of Neymar after making a £189 million offer to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona of the world record robbery three years ago?
The sensational approach has fuelled the summer transfer window as the Ligue 1 club are poised to break the world record by more than double the previous mark, with Paul Pogba returning to Manchester United last season for £89m.
After leaving, Neymar becomes the most expensive player in the world and the highest paid professional athlete in the world. PSG offers wages of more than £500,000 per week.
Barcelona are furious at the way Neymar forced his way out, although a source close to the Catalan board insists the club has always done its best to look after him since arriving from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world warned of this prospect by the PSG president three years ago?
When Manchester City expressed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi had a stern warning for any club looking to sign one of PSG's best players.
"I'm not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players, then we will be in opposition to them, we will contact their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they try to get one of our players to sign with them, there will be consequences."
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line, with the Spanish club expressing interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear that they would not allow the international from Italy to leave under any circumstances, and Barcelona could feel the consequences of that interest by losing one of their price offers for Neymar.
