Interview: "Domspatzen report exonerates Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger"
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the abuse cases exonerates Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger.
This is the opinion of author and historian Michael Hesemann.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen continues to cause discussions.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman for the reform movement "We are Church", said after publication to the German Press Agency that he expected an apology from the former Regensburg bishop and today's Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller and from the cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger, the 93-year-old brother of Pope Emeritus Benedict XVI.
It would greatly serve the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret about their own omissions or their misjudgement of the events at the time.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano", on the other hand, criticized that "double standards" were applied to the reporting of violence by the Domspatzen.
With regard to the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubts that these are "shameful and shameful acts" that must be punished and prevented in the future; What is striking, however, is the "degree of media manipulation," according to author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the Italian National Bioethics Committee.
"The habit of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evils is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider this normal," Scaraffia writes.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis also said in an interview with Bayerischer Rundfunk: "People like to go to church and that's a found food".
She also pointed out that in her youth, "beatings were a completely normal pedagogical tool to deal with naughty children like me."
She thinks it is unfair to apply today's standards to earlier decades, because the world has changed.
In connection with the reports on the abuse cases, Pope Brother Georg Ratzinger often appeared.
Completely wrongly, says author and historian Michael Hesemann, who wrote the memoirs "Mein Bruder der Papst" (My Brother the Pope) with Ratzinger (translated into 12 languages).
"I have to defend Georg Ratzinger," says Hesemann, "because none of this had anything to do with him," he says, assessing the results of the final report.
What exactly is in the 440-page report submitted by Ulrich Weber, a lawyer commissioned by the Diocese of Regensburg with the clarification?
Between 1945 and the early 1990s, a total of 547 Regensburger Domspatzen were victims of assaults "with high plausibility", 67 Domspatzen were sexually abused.
The final report on Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994, states: "In summary, it can be stated that forms of physical and psychological violence were used by Domkapellmeister R. in many cases.
Especially with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be more severe.
Nevertheless, in contrast to numerous other defendants, it is striking that many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases even associate positive memories with him despite violence."
In an interview, Hesemann explains why the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburger Domspatzen exonerates Georg Ratzinger in his opinion.
Mr. Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "Incidents of violence against wards at the Regensburger Domspatzen" gives a contradictory picture of Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students emphasize his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist, who often became violent when a Domspatz did not bring a top performance musically.
As his biographer, how do you assess this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble to read the whole 440-page report from cover to cover, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger appears in it at all.
Only eight pages are devoted to him and he is clearly absolved of any suspicion of complicity or complicity in the horrific cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of violence at the preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
At best, he can be accused of having learned about it too late or of not having taken initial hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, where he worked, was perceived by practically all respondents as - literally - "salvation", "heaven" and "better world".
The vast majority of his students also give Georg Ratzinger an excellent report, describing him as "warm-hearted", "popular", "sincere", "competent" and "understanding", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly supplied the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and was "always surrounded by grapes of children".
Only a minority complains about his perfectionism and his high emotionality, which sometimes led to outbursts of anger.
Years ago, he himself admitted that he not only slammed chairs and threw his keychain on the floor, but also handed out slaps and pulled overly cheeky boys by the hair or ears, deeply regretted and apologized for it.
To his credit, however, it must be said that such educational methods were widespread in the period in question, the 1960s and 1970s, among parents as well as teachers.
Do you also know such chastisement methods?
Of course, I think every one of us born before 1968.
I, too, experienced this in a secular school, a state grammar school.
Compared with what this report is actually about, namely the appalling sexual abuse and excessive violence in pre-school, these are, of course, trivial.
One wonders whether it is not more to do with his fame and his role as a brother of Benedict XVI. that many media pounced on him.
Many who have never understood him are still working diligently on the Bavarian Pope.
But the truth is that the report exonerates Georg Ratzinger in every respect!
In connection with the report, the media reported a great deal about the abuse of the Regensburger Domspatzen.
Is Georg Ratzinger also accused in the final report of any involvement or complicity with regard to sexual abuse?
Michael Hesemann: Clearly not.
Not a single one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have confided in the cathedral music director.
Not even the parents were informed.
"I never dared to talk to my father or mother about it," said one affected person on behalf of the others, "It was all very embarrassing for me."
The real problem in solving sexual abuse was and is that most victims remain silent out of shame.
If they did not even confide in parents and siblings, then certainly not to a choir director, who would have been a colleague of the perpetrators professionally.
How do the Domspatzen students assess Ratzinger's role with regard to the abuse cases?
Michael Hesemann: One interviewed student put it this way: "Regarding sexual abuse ... I see ... no case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) of all people would have had timely knowledge and could have stopped the respective perpetrator.
I hold it ... Also really absurd to assume that he of all people ... Boys have opened more insistently or clearly or even earlier, than towards their parents, boarding school directors, counsellors, etc.
That you talk to him about sex ... - unthinkable."
Thus, the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that affected students and/or their environment confided in him in advance could not be confirmed in the course of the investigation".
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger must therefore be acquitted of any complicity.
Thus, he cannot be accused of not having prevented him or reported him.
Therefore, there is no reason to associate one's good name with these vile crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media there was much to read about "violent excesses" at the Regensburger Domspatzen.
The former cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report of "looking away".
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem that in the reporting everything was mixed and mixed up into a huge melange of sexual abuse and violent excesses and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that, in turn, is an abuse of the report.
There is a clean separation: between the preschool and the grammar school of the Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence and, let's say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the period since 1945, i.e. also from four decades in which Georg Ratzinger was not choirmaster of the Domspatzen.
The whole terrible beating pedagogy, the cases in which boys were downright harassed and maltreated by sadistic teachers and suffered terribly from it, all took place at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where really scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But cathedral music director Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he only got to see the boys when they were already at the Domspatzengymnasium.
On it, as most witnesses emphasize, the topic of "preschool" was taboo.
One was only happy to have escaped her and enjoyed the much better treatment and for many even "paradisiacal" conditions.
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, where the report concludes that "many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases even associate positive memories with him despite violence".
So at most the accusation remains of having looked away.
However, despite all efforts, the report was only able to define two periods in which it was told about the conditions at preschool.
The first time in 1970/71, when he was just beginning to establish himself and did not want to hear anything about the events at a school where he did not work and was responsible (according to the witness), and then again around 1993.
Did Georg Ratzinger consistently close his ears to the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because already in 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Domspatzengymnasium, which the report even reproduces.
In it, he points out to them "that corporal punishment continues to be practiced in preschool".
In view of the danger of negative press publications, he recommended urgent intervention.
Of course, this was at a time when legal clarity existed, when corporal punishment had long been banned in Bavaria.
Before that, they occurred in a legal grey area, as all of us probably know.
It was also difficult for him to estimate where those affected might have exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he always looked the other way.
This is simply not true.
It was not until 1980 that corporal punishment in schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria von Thurn und Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today's pedagogical standards to that time.
What do you think?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "pitfall of anachronism", i.e. the danger of evaluating the past according to today's moral standards.
The princess is right.
But, of course, this does not apply to sexual abuse, which has always been heinous, nor to what was committed in preschool in terms of adversity and violence against innocent children's souls, which goes far beyond what was usual at the time.
This is all terrible and I am glad that it is finally being dealt with.
But at the same time I have to defend Georg Ratzinger, because none of this had anything to do with him.
His means of discipline and punishment, i.e. slapping and pulling by the hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When corporal punishment was banned, he strictly adhered to it.
What image of his time in Regensburg did Georg Ratzinger give in his conversations with you for the book "Mein Bruder der Papst"?
Was the topic of corporal punishment also discussed?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, Pope Benedict XVI., tells from his perspective, the Domspatzen played only a minor role.
Nevertheless, I do not conceal the fact that he led a strict regiment there.
But even this must be said: Without this perfectionism, without the demand for absolute discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form a world-class institution from the Regensburger Domspatzen, which until then had been rather nationally known, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, who toured twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With cookies and sweets alone you do not make great singers out of unruly boys and face every success, no matter in which field, but always discipline, passion and self-overcoming.
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger as during the discussions about your book?
Michael Hesemann: Through the work on the book and beyond, I got to know Georg Ratzinger really well and experienced him again and again as a wonderful, humorous, kind, deeply religious and good-hearted person, of whom one cannot imagine that he could harm even a fly.
I regularly see how many former Domspatzen still keep in regular contact with him today, 23 years after his retirement, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him like a member of their family.
Those who still do not forgive him for once being strict with them are clearly in the minority.
Most Domspatzen today are grateful to him for enriching their lives and introducing them to the world of music.
And that he was always a good, fatherly teacher - a strict father, certainly, that may be - but also a lovable person of respect, whom they still look up to today and whom they almost adore.
And please, once again very clearly: All he is accused of are educational methods that were the order of the day at that time.
We can be glad that we have long since overcome this time.
But it is highly unfair to scapegoat a man just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
The evil intent behind it is all too obvious.
Because the report, which has just been published, exonerates him.
Now decency would demand that a 93-year-old man, who has earned great merits and without whom no one outside Bavaria and perhaps even Germany would probably know the Regensburger Domspatzen, finally be left in peace.
